Got it üëç You want to install the **latest version of Docker Compose**.
There are **two versions** of Docker Compose now:

* **Docker Compose V1** (old, `docker-compose` command) ‚Üí **deprecated**.
* **Docker Compose V2** (new, `docker compose` command) ‚Üí **latest and recommended**.

I‚Äôll show you the **installation for Docker Compose V2** (latest).

---

## üîπ Step 1: Make sure Docker is installed

Check if Docker is installed:

```bash
docker --version
```

If not installed, first install Docker:

```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y docker.io
```

(For Amazon Linux 2: `sudo yum install -y docker`)

Start and enable Docker:

```bash
sudo systemctl enable docker
sudo systemctl start docker
```

---

## üîπ Step 2: Install Docker Compose (latest)

### Option 1: Install via Docker‚Äôs plugin system (recommended)

```bash
DOCKER_CONFIG=${DOCKER_CONFIG:-$HOME/.docker}
mkdir -p $DOCKER_CONFIG/cli-plugins

curl -SL https://github.com/docker/compose/releases/latest/download/docker-compose-$(uname -s)-$(uname -m) \
 -o $DOCKER_CONFIG/cli-plugins/docker-compose
```

Make it executable:

```bash
chmod +x $DOCKER_CONFIG/cli-plugins/docker-compose
```

---

### Option 2: Install system-wide (if you want root usage)

```bash
sudo curl -SL https://github.com/docker/compose/releases/latest/download/docker-compose-$(uname -s)-$(uname -m) \
 -o /usr/local/bin/docker-compose
```

Make it executable:

```bash
sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/docker-compose
```

---

## üîπ Step 3: Verify installation

Check version:

```bash
docker compose version
```

or

```bash
docker-compose version   # only if you installed V1 binary
```

You should see something like:

```
Docker Compose version v2.29.2
```

---

‚ö° Now you can use Docker Compose:

```bash
docker compose up -d
```

